where formula_54 is the element in formula_1 associated to formula_56.

This allows us to define the reproducing kernel of formula_1 as a function formula_58 (or formula_4 in the complex case) by

:formula_60

From this definition it is easy to see that formula_58 (or formula_4 in the complex case) is both symmetric (resp. conjugate symmetric) and positive definite, i.e.

:formula_63

for every formula_64 The Moore–Aronszajn theorem (see below) is a sort of converse to this: if a function formula_65 satisfies these conditions then there is a Hilbert space of functions on formula_2 for which it is a reproducing kernel.

