== Extension to vector-valued functions==
In this section we extend the definition of the RKHS to spaces of vector-valued functions as this extension is particularly important in multi-task learning and manifold regularization. The main difference is that the reproducing kernel formula_209 is a symmetric function that is now a positive semi-definite &quot;matrix&quot; for every formula_210 in formula_211. More formally, we define a vector-valued RKHS (vvRKHS) as a Hilbert space of functions formula_212 such that for all formula_213 and formula_111

:formula_215

and

:formula_216

This second property parallels the reproducing property for the scalar-valued case. This definition can also be connected to integral operators, bounded evaluation functions, and feature maps as we saw for the scalar-valued RKHS. We can equivalently define the vvRKHS as a vector-valued Hilbert space with a bounded evaluation functional and show that this implies the existence of a unique reproducing kernel by the Riesz Representation theorem. Mercer&#x27;s theorem can also be extended to address the vector-valued setting and we can therefore obtain a feature map view of the vvRKHS. Lastly, it can also be shown that the closure of the span of formula_217 coincides with formula_89, another property similar to the scalar-valued case.

We can gain intuition for the vvRKHS by taking a component-wise perspective on these spaces. In particular, we find that every vvRKHS is isometrically isomorphic to a scalar-valued RKHS on a particular input space. Let formula_219. Consider the space formula_220 and the corresponding reproducing kernel

As noted above, the RKHS associated to this reproducing kernel is given by the closure of the span of formula_221 where 
formula_222 for every set of pairs 

The connection to the scalar-valued RKHS can then be made by the fact that every matrix-valued kernel can be identified with a kernel of the form of () via

:formula_223

Moreover, every kernel with the form of () defines a matrix-valued kernel with the above expression. Now letting the map formula_224 be defined as

:formula_225

where formula_226 is the formula_227 component of the canonical basis for formula_228, one can show that formula_229 is bijective and an isometry between formula_230 and formula_231.

While this view of the vvRKHS can be useful in multi-task learning, this isometry does not reduce the study of the vector-valued case to that of the scalar-valued case. In fact, this isometry procedure can make both the scalar-valued kernel and the input space too difficult to work with in practice as properties of the original kernels are often lost.

An important class of matrix-valued reproducing kernels are &quot;separable&quot; kernels which can factorized as the product of a scalar valued kernel and a formula_232-dimensional symmetric positive semi-definite matrix. In light of our previous discussion these kernels are of the form

:formula_233

for all formula_234 in formula_211 and formula_236 in formula_237. As the scalar-valued kernel encodes dependencies between the inputs, we can observe that the matrix-valued kernel encodes dependencies among both the inputs and the outputs.

We lastly remark that the above theory can be further extended to spaces of functions with values in function spaces but obtaining kernels for these spaces is a more difficult task.

== Connection between RKHSs and the ReLU function ==
The ReLU function is commonly defined as formula_238 and is a mainstay in the architecture of neural networks where it is used as an activation function. One can construct a ReLU-like nonlinear function using the theory of reproducing kernel Hilbert spaces. Below, we derive this construction and show how it implies the representation power of neural networks with ReLU activations. 

We will work with the Hilbert space formula_239 of absolutely continuous functions with formula_240 and square integrable (i.e. formula_241) derivative. It has the inner product 

: formula_242

To construct the reproducing kernel it suffices to consider a dense subspace, so let formula_243 and formula_244. 
The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus then gives 

: formula_245

where

:formula_246 

and formula_247 i.e.

:formula_248

This implies formula_249 reproduces formula_10.

Moreover the minimum function on formula_251 has the following representations with the ReLu function: 

: formula_252

Using this formulation, we can apply the representer theorem to the RKHS, letting one prove the optimality of using ReLU activations in neural network settings.

